247
00:11:31.750 --> 00:11:32.976
No. I'm sorry. I'm just not that person.

248
00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.309
I'm not. Maybe I can
make something of this job.

249
00:11:35.333 --> 00:11:38.726
<i>Runway</i> does have a history
of publishing great writing.

250
00:11:38.750 --> 00:11:40.768
No. I'm gonna walk in there tomorrow

251
00:11:40.792 --> 00:11:42.601
with a big smile on my face

252
00:11:42.625 --> 00:11:46.000
and I'm going to make
something of this job. Okay?

253
00:11:56.750 --> 00:11:58.101
What?

254
00:11:58.125 --> 00:12:01.226
"Don't worry. I fixed it.
Be ready at 9:00. Irv."

255
00:12:01.250 --> 00:12:04.601
And you-know-who demanded
we be crosstown at 9:15.

256
00:12:04.625 --> 00:12:06.018
so how do we do both?

257
00:12:06.042 --> 00:12:07.684
We don't have time for this.

258
00:12:07.708 --> 00:12:09.101
What does he mean. "I fixed it"?

259
00:12:09.125 --> 00:12:10.667
[sighs] I have no idea.

260
00:12:11.333 --> 00:12:12.973
- Your 9:00 a.m. is here.
- [Miranda] Hmm.

261
00:12:14.917 --> 00:12:15.917
[gasps]

262
00:12:17.792 --> 00:12:19.042
Hello.

263
00:12:19.792 --> 00:12:20.768
Miranda.

264
00:12:20.792 --> 00:12:22.809
[gasps] Nigel.

265
00:12:22.833 --> 00:12:25.208
Look what TJ Maxx dragged in.

266
00:12:25.792 --> 00:12:28.083
- Hello. Six.
- Hello. [chuckles]

267
00:12:29.875 --> 00:12:32.893
Thank you so much for this opportunity.

268
00:12:32.917 --> 00:12:34.226
I... I've got to admit.

269
00:12:34.250 --> 00:12:36.018
I was really surprised when Irv called.

270
00:12:36.042 --> 00:12:38.500
I mean. a lot of time
has gone by. but I'm just...

271
00:12:39.625 --> 00:12:41.643
I'm so happy for the chance to...

272
00:12:41.667 --> 00:12:42.726
Sorry.

273
00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:45.018
Who is this? Do you know her?
Do I know her?

274
00:12:45.042 --> 00:12:48.893
You might remember Andy.
She was one of the Emilys.

275
00:12:48.917 --> 00:12:49.976
One of the what?

276
00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.434
- The Emily from... It's...
- I'm Andy Sachs.

277
00:12:52.458 --> 00:12:54.125
Uh... Uh. the smart fat girl.

278
00:12:55.167 --> 00:12:57.434
I was one of your assistants eons ago.

279
00:12:57.458 --> 00:12:58.726
Maybe Irv didn't fill you in.

280
00:12:58.750 --> 00:13:00.601
And Irv sent you here to...

281
00:13:00.625 --> 00:13:04.042
To run the Features department.

282
00:13:04.708 --> 00:13:07.833
Be the Features editor.
He hired me last night.

283
00:13:08.542 --> 00:13:09.583
He didn't tell you?

284
00:13:12.125 --> 00:13:13.125
Um...

285
00:13:14.917 --> 00:13:19.559
So he said that. um. we need to. um...

286
00:13:19.583 --> 00:13:23.184
I mean. <i>Runway</i> needs to take control
of the narrative of the SpeedFash story.

287
00:13:23.208 --> 00:13:25.226
and-and-and restore credibility.

288
00:13:25.250 --> 00:13:29.393
and he thought someone with my expertise
would be a good idea.

289
00:13:29.417 --> 00:13:33.518
but I thought that for sure
you had approved and were excited.

290
00:13:33.542 --> 00:13:35.018
And that's why I came in here all like...

291
00:13:35.042 --> 00:13:36.125
[singsongy] <i>♪ A-oh! ♪</i>

292
00:13:40.708 --> 00:13:42.351
- Amari.
- Yes.

293
00:13:42.375 --> 00:13:44.417
Get Ashley on the phone. please.

294
00:13:46.167 --> 00:13:47.309
[rings. clicks]

295
00:13:47.333 --> 00:13:48.733
[Ashley] <i>Hi. Good morning. Miranda.</i>

296
00:13:49.042 --> 00:13:50.643
Yes. Ashley. Flag on the play.

297
00:13:50.667 --> 00:13:53.476
We don't need you this morning or ever.

298
00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:55.184
so pack up your things.

299
00:13:55.208 --> 00:13:57.809
And HR will be in to see you shortly.

300
00:13:57.833 --> 00:13:58.726
Uh...

301
00:13:58.750 --> 00:13:59.750
Happy?

302
00:14:00.833 --> 00:14:04.000
You just cost Cornell
summa cum laude her job.

303
00:14:04.792 --> 00:14:07.708
First in her family to
go to college. I believe.

304
00:14:08.750 --> 00:14:10.226
Anyway. come along.

305
00:14:10.250 --> 00:14:11.750
[Nigel] Come on.

306
00:14:24.042 --> 00:14:25.042
[Andy] Uh...

307
00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.000
[grunts]

308
00:14:33.458 --> 00:14:35.351
You should get that looked at.

309
00:14:35.375 --> 00:14:36.309
Hmm?

310
00:14:36.333 --> 00:14:38.476
The injury. or condition. or whatever.

311
00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:40.417
that causes you to trudge.

312
00:14:41.125 --> 00:14:42.184
[Miranda sighs]

313
00:14:42.208 --> 00:14:44.809
So. um. I was thinking that...

314
00:14:44.833 --> 00:14:47.184
[clears throat] ...when we
get back to the offices.

315
00:14:47.208 --> 00:14:48.268
we could sit down

316
00:14:48.292 --> 00:14:50.643
and go through some of your priorities.

317
00:14:50.667 --> 00:14:53.893
I could share some of my insights into
the editorial direction of the magazine.

318
00:14:53.917 --> 00:14:58.601
First. though. we need to appease
an important advertiser.

319
00:14:58.625 --> 00:15:00.309
- I-Is that where we're going?
- [Nigel] Yes.

320
00:15:00.333 --> 00:15:02.184
They're furious about SpeedFash.

321
00:15:02.208 --> 00:15:05.393
[sighs] God knows what they're
going to extract from me.

322
00:15:05.417 --> 00:15:07.976
Free ad space. targeted editorial.

323
00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:09.208
A cornea.

324
00:15:09.958 --> 00:15:12.351
Luckily. though. I'm not worried

325
00:15:12.375 --> 00:15:16.143
'cause I have you flown in from on high

326
00:15:16.167 --> 00:15:19.726
to help redirect
this century-old institution

327
00:15:19.750 --> 00:15:22.559
with the benefit of
your infinite wisdom and what?

328
00:15:22.583 --> 00:15:24.708
Oh. Expertise.

329
00:15:25.417 --> 00:15:26.667
Yeah.

330
00:15:27.958 --> 00:15:32.143
Dior constitutes
16% of our designer spend.

331
00:15:32.167 --> 00:15:34.393
And are leading sponsors of
all our special events.

332
00:15:34.417 --> 00:15:35.476
which ain't cheap.

333
00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:37.434
Okay. so we fix this. we got this.

334
00:15:37.458 --> 00:15:38.583
Who do we have to talk to?

335
00:15:45.375 --> 00:15:47.042
Am I having a hallucination?

336
00:15:47.667 --> 00:15:48.708
Emily. hi.

337
00:15:49.583 --> 00:15:51.042
Oh. wow.

338
00:15:52.208 --> 00:15:54.184
You also know her?

339
00:15:54.208 --> 00:15:56.875
Well. we were at <i>Runway</i>
at the same time. Miranda.

340
00:15:57.417 --> 00:15:59.542
Really? Where was I?

341
00:16:01.542 --> 00:16:04.792
Right. Um. shall we?

342
00:16:07.333 --> 00:16:09.018
Ms. Charlton. you're glowing.

343
00:16:09.042 --> 00:16:10.851
It seems retail still suits you.

344
00:16:10.875 --> 00:16:13.601
Ah. Nigel. you're hanging in there
by your fingernails.

345
00:16:13.625 --> 00:16:15.476
Remember when magazines were a thing?

346
00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:18.625
All right. Come on in. everybody.
Take a seat.

347
00:16:19.708 --> 00:16:21.958
- Lots to discuss.
- [Nigel] Mm-hmm.

348
00:16:22.958 --> 00:16:25.042
Um... Where would you like to start?

349
00:16:25.792 --> 00:16:26.792
[sighs]

350
00:16:27.292 --> 00:16:31.059
Okay. So. um. I'm the new
Features editor at <i>Runway.</i>

351
00:16:31.083 --> 00:16:32.667
No. you're not.

352
00:16:34.292 --> 00:16:35.643
Are you serious?

353
00:16:35.667 --> 00:16:38.309
Wow. Wonders never cease.

354
00:16:38.333 --> 00:16:40.643
No. I'm actually a journalist now.

355
00:16:40.667 --> 00:16:44.226
Um. I've been published in...
It doesn't matter.

356
00:16:44.250 --> 00:16:46.476
Anyway. we are all well aware
that running that story

357
00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:48.351
was a mistake and are taking
immediate steps...

358
00:16:48.375 --> 00:16:50.000
I cannot actually get over this.

359
00:16:50.875 --> 00:16:52.476
It's really remarkable.

360
00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:56.018
A senior editor at <i>Runway.</i> You.

361
00:16:56.042 --> 00:16:57.268
Yep.

362
00:16:57.292 --> 00:16:59.726
- We're all so thrilled.
- Mm-hmm.

363
00:16:59.750 --> 00:17:03.101
You know what's funny. is you've changed.
You have. You're much more confident.

364
00:17:03.125 --> 00:17:04.018
Oh.

365
00:17:04.042 --> 00:17:06.018
[Emily] Kept those eyebrows
though. didn't you?

366
00:17:06.042 --> 00:17:09.101
Um. right. Miranda. [sighs] How are you?

367
00:17:09.125 --> 00:17:10.393
I mean. what a shambles.

368
00:17:10.417 --> 00:17:13.351
I've had to unruffle so many feathers
because as you know.

369
00:17:13.375 --> 00:17:19.268
our association with <i>Runway</i> and with you
is predicated on your sterling reputation.

370
00:17:19.292 --> 00:17:21.018
[scoffs] Momentary lapse.

371
00:17:21.042 --> 00:17:23.643
And we're doing everything we can
to make it right with you.

372
00:17:23.667 --> 00:17:25.518
Good. 'cause I was
quite shocked reading it.

373
00:17:25.542 --> 00:17:27.226
Though. I'm sure. as you can appreciate.

374
00:17:27.250 --> 00:17:29.268
it's also important that
we have editorial freedom.

375
00:17:29.292 --> 00:17:31.143
We have to maintain
our journalistic integrity.

376
00:17:31.167 --> 00:17:33.184
Ooh. Integrity. I see.

377
00:17:33.208 --> 00:17:36.059
La-di-da. Andy. Very high-minded of you.

378
00:17:36.083 --> 00:17:38.101
Well. please help yourself
to standards galore.

379
00:17:38.125 --> 00:17:41.518
but if there are no advertisers.
there's no <i>Runway.</i>

380
00:17:41.542 --> 00:17:42.851
No us. no you.

381
00:17:42.875 --> 00:17:45.768
- And we understand that completely.
- Oh. good.

382
00:17:45.792 --> 00:17:49.184
I think as a consequence
of your lapse in judgment.

383
00:17:49.208 --> 00:17:52.268
there's just a few things we'd quite like
just to smooth it all over.

384
00:17:52.292 --> 00:17:55.893
We are thinking at least three pages
of advertising credit

385
00:17:55.917 --> 00:17:59.167
and a feature on the opening
of our new flagship.

386
00:17:59.708 --> 00:18:00.976
- Six pages.
- Three.

387
00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:02.059
No. Five.

388
00:18:02.083 --> 00:18:03.018
Four.

389
00:18:03.042 --> 00:18:05.268
I'm sorry. Are we at a fish market. Nigel?

390
00:18:05.292 --> 00:18:08.292
It's five. with brand mentions
in all captions.

391
00:18:09.750 --> 00:18:11.018
Miranda?

392
00:18:11.042 --> 00:18:14.143
Absolutely. We'll get
right on that immediately.

393
00:18:14.167 --> 00:18:15.167
[Emily] Great.

394
00:18:21.292 --> 00:18:23.875
I'm confused. You just
let them tell you what to do?

395
00:18:24.500 --> 00:18:25.684
Because if I'm here

396
00:18:25.708 --> 00:18:27.434
to restore your credibility. and I...

397
00:18:27.458 --> 00:18:30.351
Did you not hear her? No them. no us.

398
00:18:30.375 --> 00:18:32.059
We need our advertisers. Andrea.

399
00:18:32.083 --> 00:18:34.976
The September issue is already so thin
you could floss with it.

400
00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:36.768
Yeah. advertisers are important.

401
00:18:36.792 --> 00:18:38.851
I know that. I'm not brand-new. but...

402
00:18:38.875 --> 00:18:40.083
Let's be clear.

403
00:18:41.333 --> 00:18:43.809
You did not earn this job.
I did not hire you.

404
00:18:43.833 --> 00:18:47.268
You are a CEO's latest whim.

405
00:18:47.292 --> 00:18:50.542
And all I need to do is to
bide my time until you fail.

406
00:18:52.250 --> 00:18:54.333
And you will. Fail.

407
00:18:57.833 --> 00:18:59.333
Why don't you take the train. dear?

408
00:19:24.917 --> 00:19:26.851
You got this. You got this.

409
00:19:26.875 --> 00:19:28.542
You... did it.

410
00:19:29.625 --> 00:19:30.684
Okay.

411
00:19:30.708 --> 00:19:31.958
[sighs]

412
00:19:33.208 --> 00:19:34.208
[keys clatter]

413
00:19:36.792 --> 00:19:38.292
They're just eyebrows.

414
00:19:39.292 --> 00:19:41.125
[♪ Upbeat music playing]

415
00:19:47.667 --> 00:19:48.976
[elevator bell dings]

416
00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:50.500
[staff chattering]

417
00:20:01.333 --> 00:20:02.434
- Hi!
- Hi.

418
00:20:02.458 --> 00:20:03.976
We weren't properly introduced yesterday.

419
00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:05.059
I'm Andy Sachs.

420
00:20:05.083 --> 00:20:06.601
Charlie. I'm the second assistant.

421
00:20:06.625 --> 00:20:07.518
Hi. Charlie!

422
00:20:07.542 --> 00:20:10.059
Hey. Everybody just calls me
"Charlie the Chair." if you want.

423
00:20:10.083 --> 00:20:11.683
'cause Amari won't let me leave my desk.

424
00:20:12.083 --> 00:20:13.018
Oh. no. it's okay.

425
00:20:13.042 --> 00:20:14.768
[chuckles] A million girls
would kill for this job.

426
00:20:14.792 --> 00:20:16.559
Heard that. [chuckles]

427
00:20:16.583 --> 00:20:17.875
- Is Miranda in?
- There you are.

428
00:20:18.458 --> 00:20:20.934
There you are. I am on time.

429
00:20:20.958 --> 00:20:21.934
So... [scoffs]

430
00:20:21.958 --> 00:20:24.268
You're the kind of person
who thinks on time is on time.

431
00:20:24.292 --> 00:20:25.184
Okay. got it.

432
00:20:25.208 --> 00:20:27.018
All right. come on.
I'll show you to your office.

433
00:20:27.042 --> 00:20:30.143
Amari. I need to pee.
Please. I had a venti.

434
00:20:30.167 --> 00:20:31.268
Oh.

435
00:20:31.292 --> 00:20:32.768
Was it worth it?

436
00:20:32.792 --> 00:20:33.768
- No.
- No.

437
00:20:33.792 --> 00:20:35.809
Actually. I should probably
talk to Miranda first.

438
00:20:35.833 --> 00:20:37.333
Oh. I'll take you to your office.

439
00:20:38.042 --> 00:20:40.500
- Good luck. Charlie.
- Thanks.

440
00:20:41.042 --> 00:20:42.559
So. I used to have your job.

441
00:20:42.583 --> 00:20:44.476
I heard. Such a remarkable fact.

442
00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:47.601
Yeah. back in 2006.

443
00:20:47.625 --> 00:20:49.434
[chuckles] Got to go
to Paris Fashion Week.

444
00:20:49.458 --> 00:20:51.059
Wore a bunch of pieces
from the Chanel collection

445
00:20:51.083 --> 00:20:52.018
that year.

446
00:20:52.042 --> 00:20:54.226
Oh. wait. The one with the pageboy hats?

447
00:20:54.250 --> 00:20:56.268
And the thigh-high boots. Yeah!

448
00:20:56.292 --> 00:20:57.768
Love. Do you still have all of it?

449
00:20:57.792 --> 00:20:59.768
- No. I gave it away.
- What?

450
00:20:59.792 --> 00:21:01.625
Would've been a bit much for a newsroom.

451
00:21:03.917 --> 00:21:04.976
This is you.

452
00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:06.417
Oh. Okay.

453
00:21:13.333 --> 00:21:14.476
And this was Ashley's office?

454
00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:17.059
No. Miranda wanted you to have this one.
for some reason.

455
00:21:17.083 --> 00:21:18.250
For some reason. Right.

456
00:21:19.375 --> 00:21:20.875
Who gives away Chanel?

457
00:21:31.292 --> 00:21:32.542
- I stole these for you.
- Hey.

458
00:21:33.292 --> 00:21:34.768
- All from this season.
- [gasps]

459
00:21:34.792 --> 00:21:36.833
But lie about where you got them.

460
00:21:37.333 --> 00:21:39.708
There's more where that came from.
but you can't be greedy.

461
00:21:40.458 --> 00:21:42.851
- Cafeteria?
- Great. I'm all done.

462
00:21:42.875 --> 00:21:43.875
Come on.

463
00:21:44.500 --> 00:21:45.500
Hmm.

464
00:21:45.917 --> 00:21:49.018
I don't mind that blazer. Is it...

465
00:21:49.042 --> 00:21:50.726
- Margiela.
- Huh.

466
00:21:50.750 --> 00:21:53.476
Thrifted it in Provo. Eleven bucks.

467
00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:55.309
Learned a thing or two the
last time I was here. babe.

468
00:21:55.333 --> 00:21:57.643
Hmm! Not bad. babe.

469
00:21:57.667 --> 00:21:59.268
[Jamiroquai "Diskokid" playing]

470
00:21:59.292 --> 00:22:01.018
Ah. fate.

471
00:22:01.042 --> 00:22:03.434
The winding road
that brings us back to me.

472
00:22:03.458 --> 00:22:05.851
watching you ladle goo into a bowl.

473
00:22:05.875 --> 00:22:07.083
[chuckles]

474
00:22:08.125 --> 00:22:09.601
It's so good to see you. Nigel.

475
00:22:09.625 --> 00:22:10.809
Yeah.

476
00:22:10.833 --> 00:22:13.042
Miranda is very lucky
you're still at the magazine.

477
00:22:14.125 --> 00:22:15.226
What magazine?

478
00:22:15.250 --> 00:22:19.184
You must know that <i>Runway</i>
stopped being a magazine many years ago.

479
00:22:19.208 --> 00:22:22.601
I mean. we still have a book.
but practically nobody buys it.

480
00:22:22.625 --> 00:22:25.434
Nope. We are digital. We are download able.

481
00:22:25.458 --> 00:22:27.542
We are stream able. We're in the ether.

482
00:22:28.917 --> 00:22:30.018
And the budgets?

483
00:22:30.042 --> 00:22:33.226
I used to get four weeks
in Africa with Avedon

484
00:22:33.250 --> 00:22:34.518
to do a glossy spread.

485
00:22:34.542 --> 00:22:38.351
and now I'm lucky if I get
two days at Milk Studios

486
00:22:38.375 --> 00:22:43.125
to shoot content that people
scroll past whilst they pee.

487
00:22:46.083 --> 00:22:46.976
[groans]

488
00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:48.417
- So...
- Yeah?

489
00:22:49.333 --> 00:22:54.101
Is it just me. or has Miranda
been extra spicy?

490
00:22:54.125 --> 00:22:55.934
You see her outside of Dior?

491
00:22:55.958 --> 00:22:57.976
I thought her head was going
to spin completely around.

492
00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:01.143
Well. she's on edge
because Irv is about to promote her

493
00:23:01.167 --> 00:23:02.684
to Global Head of Content.

494
00:23:02.708 --> 00:23:04.226
- No way. That's a huge job.
- Yeah.

495
00:23:04.250 --> 00:23:05.184
But the problem is.

496
00:23:05.208 --> 00:23:08.434
the SpeedFash debacle
might derail the whole thing.

497
00:23:08.458 --> 00:23:11.768
What you're saying is. she needs me.

498
00:23:11.792 --> 00:23:13.292
[chuckles]

499
00:23:17.458 --> 00:23:19.434
- Oh. you're serious.
- [chokes]

500
00:23:19.458 --> 00:23:20.351
Sorry.

501
00:23:20.375 --> 00:23:21.268
- Oh. really.
- Yeah.

502
00:23:21.292 --> 00:23:22.351
I'm going up to the art department.

503
00:23:22.375 --> 00:23:24.184
- Oh. you like that.
- [laughing] Yeah. very much.

504
00:23:24.208 --> 00:23:25.351
- Are you Andy?
- Yes.

505
00:23:25.375 --> 00:23:27.143
Hi. I'm Jin Chao. I'm your new assistant.

506
00:23:27.167 --> 00:23:28.226
- Cool! I was wondering...
- Hi.

507
00:23:28.250 --> 00:23:29.726
About that. Nice to meet you.

508
00:23:29.750 --> 00:23:32.351
I was an intern this morning.
but. uh. when a desk opens up.

509
00:23:32.375 --> 00:23:34.851
the interns get a chance to interview.
and guess what?

510
00:23:34.875 --> 00:23:37.643
Nobody wanted to work in your department
'cause it's not actual fashion.

511
00:23:37.667 --> 00:23:39.768
so I just. like. got it. Isn't that cool?

512
00:23:39.792 --> 00:23:40.684
Very.

513
00:23:40.708 --> 00:23:43.184
- You don't want me.
- [stammers] I didn't say that.

514
00:23:43.208 --> 00:23:44.976
If you don't want me. you can
interview someone else.

515
00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:46.268
- That's totally fine.
- I don't...

516
00:23:46.292 --> 00:23:47.934
I did go to Yale. 3.86 GPA.

517
00:23:47.958 --> 00:23:49.226
lead soprano of the Whiffenpoofs.

518
00:23:49.250 --> 00:23:51.684
and my ACT score was 36
on the very first try. but...

519
00:23:51.708 --> 00:23:53.476
No. you seem great. I'm happy to have you.

520
00:23:53.500 --> 00:23:54.893
- Great. Okay. Nice.
- Okay. great. Okay.

521
00:23:54.917 --> 00:23:56.643
Um. so. listen. I'm going
to be working late tonight.

522
00:23:56.667 --> 00:23:59.083
so I'm just going to need
a couple things. First. I j...

523
00:24:00.375 --> 00:24:02.833
Is Miranda hanging up her own coat?

524
00:24:03.875 --> 00:24:06.268
Oh. yeah. I heard there were
some HR complaints.

525
00:24:06.292 --> 00:24:09.643
Apparently. she used to
just throw her coat at people.

526
00:24:09.667 --> 00:24:10.684
Huh.

527
00:24:10.708 --> 00:24:11.708
[closet door slams]

528
00:24:15.375 --> 00:24:16.542
[exhales deeply]

529
00:24:19.917 --> 00:24:21.417
Maybe some things have changed.

530
00:24:22.292 --> 00:24:24.393
Ah. Anyway. yes. working late tonight.

531
00:24:24.417 --> 00:24:25.917
[chattering]

532
00:24:28.583 --> 00:24:30.750
[Andy muttering indistinctly]

533
00:24:40.667 --> 00:24:42.726
You're not still waiting for
the book. are you?

534
00:24:42.750 --> 00:24:44.768
Oh. yeah. She likes hard copies.

535
00:24:44.792 --> 00:24:46.184
[sighs] Still?

536
00:24:46.208 --> 00:24:47.476
[chuckles] Mm-hmm.

537
00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:49.684
Um. can I give you something
to bring over to her?

538
00:24:49.708 --> 00:24:51.059
'Course. I'll hoof it over.

539
00:24:51.083 --> 00:24:52.184
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

540
00:24:52.208 --> 00:24:53.934
Oh. When you go to her house.

541
00:24:53.958 --> 00:24:55.625
no matter what anyone tells you.

542
00:24:56.125 --> 00:24:58.143
don't go up the stairs. ever.

543
00:24:58.167 --> 00:24:59.059
[chuckles]

544
00:24:59.083 --> 00:25:00.309
Who'd be stupid enough to do that?

545
00:25:00.333 --> 00:25:01.333
No one!

546
00:25:07.417 --> 00:25:08.625
[phone buzzes]

547
00:25:17.833 --> 00:25:18.833
[chuckles]

548
00:25:26.417 --> 00:25:28.018
Vanessa Friedman in <i>The Times</i>

549
00:25:28.042 --> 00:25:31.393
says that Andy's story
is a "bracing mea culpa."

550
00:25:31.417 --> 00:25:34.393
Yeah. but did anyone
besides culture writers

551
00:25:34.417 --> 00:25:36.059
actually click on the story?

552
00:25:36.083 --> 00:25:39.893
Not really. but optics-wise.
saved our bacon. right?

553
00:25:39.917 --> 00:25:41.417
We'll see. Jury's still out.

554
00:25:44.375 --> 00:25:46.042
[♪ Upbeat music playing]

555
00:25:51.458 --> 00:25:52.833
- Good morning.
- Hi.

556
00:25:58.667 --> 00:25:59.708
Nigel in?

557
00:26:00.208 --> 00:26:02.208
No. Nigel's not in.

558
00:26:08.375 --> 00:26:09.434
- I read your piece.
- Hmm?

559
00:26:09.458 --> 00:26:10.809
I read your piece. It was really good.

560
00:26:10.833 --> 00:26:12.500
Oh. thank you. [chuckles]

561
00:26:13.500 --> 00:26:15.684
Oh. See. that was a cool profile.

562
00:26:15.708 --> 00:26:17.893
Oh. yeah. The Barnes piece.

563
00:26:17.917 --> 00:26:20.643
Obviously. it was from before their split.

564
00:26:20.667 --> 00:26:21.643
Yeah.

565
00:26:21.667 --> 00:26:23.476
- I love Sasha Barnes.
- I know.

566
00:26:23.500 --> 00:26:24.809
[Andy] I've tried to get
an interview with her.

567
00:26:24.833 --> 00:26:26.851
like. a million times
but I've always struck out.

568
00:26:26.875 --> 00:26:28.934
- Oh. you're not the only one.
- Really?

569
00:26:28.958 --> 00:26:30.184
Miranda would kill.

570
00:26:30.208 --> 00:26:33.309
Now that their divorce has made Sasha
one of the richest women in the world.

571
00:26:33.333 --> 00:26:34.893
Interesting.

572
00:26:34.917 --> 00:26:37.643
I feel like I could write a book about
just his before and after.

573
00:26:37.667 --> 00:26:38.726
You know what I mean?

574
00:26:38.750 --> 00:26:40.518
The original Benji Barnes was.
like. that slope-shouldered

575
00:26:40.542 --> 00:26:43.851
nerd who's like. never seen
the inside of a weight room.

576
00:26:43.875 --> 00:26:45.643
Lately... There was a picture
of him the other day.

577
00:26:45.667 --> 00:26:50.101
A few steroids. a smidge
of Sculptra. some Ozempic

578
00:26:50.125 --> 00:26:51.643
- and voilà.
- He's a modern miracle.

579
00:26:51.667 --> 00:26:53.018
It's a modern miracle.

580
00:26:53.042 --> 00:26:54.309
Gotta love a glow up.

581
00:26:54.333 --> 00:26:55.333
It's compelling.

582
00:26:56.500 --> 00:26:58.917
Okay. well... Ooh. Hi.

583
00:27:05.500 --> 00:27:08.309
We took some vintage Muglers
and Westwoods.

584
00:27:08.333 --> 00:27:11.101
and we shot them downtown
in the Washington Mews.

585
00:27:11.125 --> 00:27:12.208
And you were there

586
00:27:12.958 --> 00:27:14.792
when these images were taken?

587
00:27:15.750 --> 00:27:17.018
Uh...

588
00:27:17.042 --> 00:27:18.893
Yes. I-I was.

589
00:27:18.917 --> 00:27:21.684
So the intention was dull and listless.

590
00:27:21.708 --> 00:27:24.684
I wouldn't say that was.
um. the goal. [titters]

591
00:27:24.708 --> 00:27:30.018
And the models were encouraged
to mill around like starving goats

592
00:27:30.042 --> 00:27:33.851
in the parking lot of a methadone clinic
in New Jersey.

593
00:27:33.875 --> 00:27:34.893
[Amari clears throat]

594
00:27:34.917 --> 00:27:36.351
- What?
- Can't say that.

595
00:27:36.375 --> 00:27:37.726
What am I not allowed to say?

596
00:27:37.750 --> 00:27:39.059
- Methadone?
- [Amari] Mmm.

597
00:27:39.083 --> 00:27:41.184
New Jersey? [chuckles]

598
00:27:41.208 --> 00:27:42.101
Anyway...

599
00:27:42.125 --> 00:27:44.309
This was our first time using
this photographer.

600
00:27:44.333 --> 00:27:45.518
so we can do a reshoot.

601
00:27:45.542 --> 00:27:47.208
Just. you know. fix it.

602
00:27:48.208 --> 00:27:52.809
So. who else? Marta?
What do you have cooking?

603
00:27:52.833 --> 00:27:55.268
We're seeing a lot of gorpcore
for this year's resort.

604
00:27:55.292 --> 00:27:59.518
so I was thinking of doing an
interactive piece on the app

605
00:27:59.542 --> 00:28:01.268
where you choose a National Park

606
00:28:01.292 --> 00:28:04.559
and then you choose
a hiking shoe and a bum bag.

607
00:28:04.583 --> 00:28:06.434
A bum bag!

608
00:28:06.458 --> 00:28:09.226
May my suicide be brief and painless.

609
00:28:09.250 --> 00:28:10.184
[Amari clears throat]

610
00:28:10.208 --> 00:28:11.768
- No. no.
- What?

611
00:28:11.792 --> 00:28:12.851
What do you mean. "No. no."

612
00:28:12.875 --> 00:28:16.917
I... I'm not talking about
killing other people. Yet.

613
00:28:18.708 --> 00:28:22.351
Okay. Fine. Uh. who else?

614
00:28:22.375 --> 00:28:23.476
Ilana. what do you have?

615
00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:27.351
The re-report of the SpeedFash
story went over well.

616
00:28:27.375 --> 00:28:30.893
Media critics responded to our candor

617
00:28:30.917 --> 00:28:33.184
and to us taking responsibility.

618
00:28:33.208 --> 00:28:36.684
Right. But did anyone read the piece?

619
00:28:36.708 --> 00:28:37.809
I don't know.

620
00:28:37.833 --> 00:28:39.667
Nigel. how are the metrics on that one?

621
00:28:40.208 --> 00:28:42.042
- [Nigel] Mm-mmm.
- Hmm-mmm.

622
00:28:42.667 --> 00:28:48.101
See. you are here to write and edit
features that people read.

623
00:28:48.125 --> 00:28:51.458
And when that happens. yes.
you may interrupt a meeting.

624
00:28:52.208 --> 00:28:54.958
But until then... [winces]

625
00:28:55.958 --> 00:28:57.208
Mm-mmm.

626
00:28:58.583 --> 00:29:02.559
Let's talk about rodeo bow ties.

627
00:29:02.583 --> 00:29:03.583
This one's cute.

628
00:29:05.333 --> 00:29:06.458
That was kinda rough.

629
00:29:06.958 --> 00:29:09.518
I mean. I just steered us
through a crisis.

630
00:29:09.542 --> 00:29:11.226
Is it so hard to acknowledge that?

631
00:29:11.250 --> 00:29:14.226
Oh. yes. The girl who likes validation.

632
00:29:14.250 --> 00:29:15.434
Did your parents hang

633
00:29:15.458 --> 00:29:17.393
all of your finger paintings
up on the fridge?

634
00:29:17.417 --> 00:29:18.643
No. It's not that.

635
00:29:18.667 --> 00:29:19.976
I don't need a pat on the head.

636
00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.518
I-I-I need to know what she wants.

637
00:29:22.542 --> 00:29:24.726
All right. I need constructive feedback.

638
00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:26.101
Oh. feedback.

639
00:29:26.125 --> 00:29:29.042
And a lollipop. or... just feedback?

640
00:29:30.458 --> 00:29:31.667
Did you need this job?

641
00:29:32.792 --> 00:29:34.208
Did you take the job?

642
00:29:35.083 --> 00:29:37.143
So figure out a way to do this job.

643
00:29:37.167 --> 00:29:38.684
- Bye.
- Bye.

644
00:29:38.708 --> 00:29:40.375
[Nigel] Bye.

645
00:30:11.292 --> 00:30:13.351
Okay. so I think that if
we're talking about...

646
00:30:13.375 --> 00:30:14.768
Kind of follow that sartorial thing

647
00:30:14.792 --> 00:30:16.000
and how it links up to...

648
00:30:29.875 --> 00:30:30.958
[groans]

649
00:30:41.292 --> 00:30:43.143
What is this?

650
00:30:43.167 --> 00:30:44.601
Oh. that's far too pink. Ken.

651
00:30:44.625 --> 00:30:45.601
We are subtle.

652
00:30:45.625 --> 00:30:47.268
We're not Valentino.
do you know what I mean?

653
00:30:47.292 --> 00:30:49.643
Is this the sample I sent you?
"Tulip whisper."

654
00:30:49.667 --> 00:30:50.667
That's the one.

655
00:30:51.625 --> 00:30:54.018
Now I don't know. I don't know about that.

656
00:30:54.042 --> 00:30:55.351
Wow.

657
00:30:55.375 --> 00:30:56.917
Oh. there she is.

658
00:30:57.667 --> 00:30:58.726
Is this all you?

659
00:30:58.750 --> 00:31:00.934
- It is.
- It's impressive.

660
00:31:00.958 --> 00:31:03.351
You are very busy.
Thank you for your time.

661
00:31:03.375 --> 00:31:06.768
The thinking is that we will
cover the new flagship.

662
00:31:06.792 --> 00:31:08.476
and your role in putting it together.

663
00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:09.684
Is that Miranda's idea?

664
00:31:09.708 --> 00:31:11.000
Um. it was mine.

665
00:31:11.792 --> 00:31:13.893
Fine. If that's what you think
is best. then that...

666
00:31:13.917 --> 00:31:15.018
That's fine.

667
00:31:15.042 --> 00:31:16.518
Okay. great. Why don't you.
uh. give me a tour.

668
00:31:16.542 --> 00:31:17.434
Okay. Will do.

669
00:31:17.458 --> 00:31:20.309
Ken. it is not a whisper.
It's a cry for help.

670
00:31:20.333 --> 00:31:22.976
This. of course. is a tribute to
the grand staircase

671
00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:26.768
at the original Dior Atelier
on Avenue Montaigne.

672
00:31:26.792 --> 00:31:28.809
- [Andy] This is incredible.
- I know.

673
00:31:28.833 --> 00:31:30.393
And the cost?

674
00:31:30.417 --> 00:31:32.226
I'm not at liberty to discuss that. Andy.

675
00:31:32.250 --> 00:31:34.351
- but it is whopping.
- [snorts]

676
00:31:34.375 --> 00:31:36.184
What? What is that sickening look?

677
00:31:36.208 --> 00:31:39.726
It's just... It's nice
to see you all grown up.

678
00:31:39.750 --> 00:31:41.726
Ugh. So... So gooey.

679
00:31:41.750 --> 00:31:44.184
Always when you used to make that face...

680
00:31:44.208 --> 00:31:45.726
Because you were always so irritating.

681
00:31:45.750 --> 00:31:47.768
Yeah. you were a barrel of fun.

682
00:31:47.792 --> 00:31:49.893
No. hey. hey. hey. Listen.

683
00:31:49.917 --> 00:31:51.434
I don't know. It's nice to see you again.

684
00:31:51.458 --> 00:31:53.143
- Catch me up. Who are you now?
- No.

685
00:31:53.167 --> 00:31:56.601
Like. not for this. just. human to human.

686
00:31:56.625 --> 00:32:00.393
Fine. I am divorced from
a pathological narcissist. Thank God.

687
00:32:00.417 --> 00:32:01.559
But I've got two beautiful children.

688
00:32:01.583 --> 00:32:02.476
Bronwyn and Roark.

689
00:32:02.500 --> 00:32:03.820
One at Collegiate. one at Chapin.

690
00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:05.976
- [Andy] Good for you.
- I know. Gorgeous. right?

691
00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:07.351
- Yeah.
- You?

692
00:32:07.375 --> 00:32:10.601
I... left New York for 15 years.

693
00:32:10.625 --> 00:32:13.667
Just lived everywhere. chasing stories.

694
00:32:14.250 --> 00:32:17.250
And I'm not married.
Never found the right person.

695
00:32:17.750 --> 00:32:20.708
And my kids are
at a doctor's office on 85th.

696
00:32:21.208 --> 00:32:22.393
They're frozen eggs right now.

697
00:32:22.417 --> 00:32:24.018
but I like to think of them
as my little ones.

698
00:32:24.042 --> 00:32:25.309
Siobhan and Esther.

699
00:32:25.333 --> 00:32:26.518
[strained chuckle]

700
00:32:26.542 --> 00:32:27.768
Okay. why did you leave <i>Runway</i>?

701
00:32:27.792 --> 00:32:29.309
I'm sorry. is this an exposé?

702
00:32:29.333 --> 00:32:31.226
- No. it's just a question.
- It's not really relevant.

703
00:32:31.250 --> 00:32:34.101
Well. I mean. you worshipped
that place. and Miranda.

704
00:32:34.125 --> 00:32:35.726
So. why'd you leave?

705
00:32:35.750 --> 00:32:37.393
Why are you even asking me why?

706
00:32:37.417 --> 00:32:39.226
I mean. have a perv around this place.

707
00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:42.434
Luxury retail is the only
sector of the fashion business

708
00:32:42.458 --> 00:32:44.601
that still makes money. That's it. Retail.

709
00:32:44.625 --> 00:32:45.684
Everything else. forget it.

710
00:32:45.708 --> 00:32:48.226
So. yes. Happy to be here. frankly.

711
00:32:48.250 --> 00:32:52.393
Because do you know that 20 years ago.
a $100 handbag was considered a splurge?

712
00:32:52.417 --> 00:32:53.857
Brands like us. we changed all that.

713
00:32:54.417 --> 00:32:58.143
Used logos and branding
because everyone understands.

714
00:32:58.167 --> 00:32:59.476
everyone gets it.

715
00:32:59.500 --> 00:33:02.726
that your bag. your scarf.
your perfume. your umbrella...

716
00:33:02.750 --> 00:33:03.643
Write this down.

717
00:33:03.667 --> 00:33:06.643
It tells the world who
you are. what you care about.

718
00:33:06.667 --> 00:33:09.184
And now. there's housewives in Banff

719
00:33:09.208 --> 00:33:12.018
who wouldn't dream of going out
without one of our $3.000 totes.

720
00:33:12.042 --> 00:33:13.059
And that's a good thing?

721
00:33:13.083 --> 00:33:15.768
I don't know. Is it a bad thing
to bring beauty and design to everyone?

722
00:33:15.792 --> 00:33:18.143
Everyone who has $3.000.

723
00:33:18.167 --> 00:33:19.583
Have you heard of Christmas?

724
00:33:20.375 --> 00:33:22.976
Anyway. don't you worry
about me and my career.

725
00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:24.042
Worry about yourself.

726
00:33:24.708 --> 00:33:26.893
I haven't seen any of your
stories get any traction.

727
00:33:26.917 --> 00:33:28.750
Nothing moving the needle there.

728
00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:30.917
What does Miranda say about it?

729
00:33:31.917 --> 00:33:33.083
Is she being tough on you?

730
00:33:35.542 --> 00:33:37.583
It's normal Miranda stuff.

731
00:33:38.208 --> 00:33:43.143
Yes. Irv. Yes. I am looking at
the numbers as we speak.

732
00:33:43.167 --> 00:33:44.226
[Irv] <i>They're unacceptable.</i>

733
00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:45.809
- <i>Take care of it!</i>
- Okay. I...

734
00:33:45.833 --> 00:33:46.833
[beeping]

735
00:33:48.167 --> 00:33:49.167
[sighs]

736
00:33:49.792 --> 00:33:51.559
Well. that sounded like a warm bath.

737
00:33:51.583 --> 00:33:55.250
[sighs] It's as if he forgets
he hired her.

738
00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:58.934
His hire. my problem.

739
00:33:58.958 --> 00:34:02.768
Did he say anything at all
about the global editorial job?

740
00:34:02.792 --> 00:34:05.268
No. he's gone mum about all that.

741
00:34:05.292 --> 00:34:07.976
I've spent my career trying to figure out
what people need to know.

742
00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:09.809
now I need to figure out
what people wanna click on.

743
00:34:09.833 --> 00:34:10.893
It's just...

744
00:34:10.917 --> 00:34:13.809
Maybe you just have to figure out
how to do those things at the same time.

745
00:34:13.833 --> 00:34:16.625
You know. like. the smart stuff
and the fun stuff.

746
00:34:17.167 --> 00:34:18.167
Oh. my God.

747
00:34:19.042 --> 00:34:22.268
Hi. there. Hi.
Uh. would you like. uh. uh...

748
00:34:22.292 --> 00:34:25.167
No. Not going to sit.

749
00:34:25.667 --> 00:34:28.434
Um. Irv called frustrated.

750
00:34:28.458 --> 00:34:31.417
